In React, the `ref` system gives you a powerful way to directly interact with specific DOM elements. It's incredibly useful for certain cases where declarative approaches fall short. We already cover about `ref` [here](https://www.codechef.com/learn/course/react-js/CREACT013/problems/PREACT050). 

Now letÔÇÖs imagine we built a custom component to ÔÇťpackageÔÇŁ an input with some extra fancy styles or labels. LetÔÇÖs call this custom component `InputWithLabel`.

```jsx
function InputWithLabel({ label, ...props }) {
  return (

      {label}


  );
}
```

We want to use it like this:

```jsx
function App() {
  const usernameRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    usernameRef.current.focus(); // ÔŁî breaks!
  }, []);

  return ;
}
```

In our IDE, this code is already written. You can run the code, and in App.jsx, simply uncomment the 10th line: `// console.log(usernameRef);` and check the `usernameRef.current` value in our console\
Oops it is null, code doesn't work as expected. But why is usernameRef.current null/undefined?



**The issue with `ref` on custom components (in React 18 and earlier)**

In versions of React before 19, a `ref` only works on **native elements** like ``, ``, or ``. When you apply a `ref` to your own custom component (like `InputWithLabel`), React treats it differently ÔÇö it gives you a reference to the **component function itself**, not the real DOM node inside.

Function components like `InputWithLabel` donÔÇÖt have any `.focus()` method ÔÇö so calling it throws an error.


#### How to solve it: `React.forwardRef`

To make a custom component accept a `ref` and forward it to one of its inner DOM elements, we use `React.forwardRef`.\
HereÔÇÖs how we fix the `InputWithLabel` component:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

const InputWithLabel = React.forwardRef(function InputWithLabel({ label, ...rest }, ref) {
  return (

      {label}


  );
});
```

Now the `ref` is passed into this component as a second argument, and we decide where to forward it. Here, weÔÇÖre forwarding it to the `` inside.

And back in the main app:

```jsx
function App() {
  const usernameRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    usernameRef.current.focus(); // Ôťů works!
  }, []);

  return ;
}
```

And boom ÔÇö now everything works as expected!


**Why not make this the default behavior?**

You might wonder: if this is such a common thing, why doesnÔÇÖt React just make it default?

Well, in earlier versions of React, `ref` could be used to get entire class-based component instances ÔÇö and changing how refs behave by default would have broken a lot of old code. Instead, React decided to require **explicit opt-in** using `forwardRef`.

But good newsÔÇŽ

#### In React 19: Refs Just WorkÔäó´ŞĆ

React 19 improves this! With the new version, you can **pass a `ref` just like any other prop**, without needing `forwardRef`. Much simpler!\
HereÔÇÖs how your component would look in React 19:

```jsx
function InputWithLabel({ label, ref, ...props }) {
  return (

      {label}


  );
}
```

